<p class="hcp3">Step 6 of 6:</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">One can <a title="Click here to read about Evidence." href="Evidence_cont.htm" id="a1" target="_self" class="hcp4">apply 
 evidence</a> to a model to gain extra insight not only into the scenario 
 you are modeling but also, in some cases, into the validity of your model 
 itself. &nbsp;If 
 Tony Soprano was really to kill Salvatore, we can imagine that Salvatore’s 
 wife would probably file a missing person report with the police after 
 several days without seeing him. &nbsp;Let’s 
 add this to our model.</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">Add a new event called “Missing person 
 report” applied to “Salvatore’s wife.” &nbsp;Create 
 a causal mechanism from “Commit murder” to the new event. &nbsp;Mechanisms 
 explain the causal relationship between events, so name this mechanism 
 something like “not seen.” &nbsp;Now, 
 to specify the probability that she will file the report if Salvatore 
 is missing, once again right click on “Missing person report”, select 
 Edit Event, and return to the Specified Probabilities tab. &nbsp;There 
 will only be one incoming cause, so set the alone column to 0.9. &nbsp;This 
 says that if Salvatore is not seen, there is a 90% chance she will file 
 a report.</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">However, it will take several days before 
 Salvatore’s disappearance to be suspicious. &nbsp;Let’s 
 put a delay on the “not seen” mechanism to model this. &nbsp;Right 
 click on mechanism and select Timing. &nbsp;Enter 
 in 5 as the value for delay; this means that a change in the cause will 
 trigger the mechanism 5 timesteps later.</p>
